GOAL V01 • You can describe what an embedded real-time system is, how it can be built and what challenges may arise in such systems.
GOAL V01 • You gain a basic understanding of the modelling process and the system structure of the underlying embedded hardware and software layers (programmed in C/C++).

GOAL L01 • You can set up a C++ project in STM32CubeIDE from scratch.
GOAL L01 • You can add libraries to your project and configure them properly.
GOAL L01 • You can write C code that is callable from C++.
GOAL L01 • You can write a C++ application and call it from C.
GOAL L01 • You understand the general structure of a C++ project.


GOAL V02 • You can explain the functionality and purpose of an embedded real-time operating system (RTOS), how it is built and how it relates to a “bare metal” implementation (pros and cons).
GOAL V02 • You can explain the underlying concepts and mechanisms related to an RTOS’s task management, including tasks/ processes, process states, task/context switches and scheduling/dispatching.
GOAL V02 • You can explain the principles of multitasking and concurrency.
GOAL V02 • You can understand and utilize a selected RTOS, the FreeRTOS, to create and manage tasks.

GOAL Lab 02 • You can understand the basics of a scheduler and a dispatcher, as well as how they relate to each other.
GOAL Lab 02 • You can implement a simple tasker on your own.
GOAL Lab 02 • You can explain what a task is and how it basically works.
GOAL Lab 02 • You can write new C++ classes from a given UML diagram specification.

<!-- Lab 03: FreeRTOS Task Management -->
GOAL L03 • You can create multiple tasks in FreeRTOS.
GOAL L03 • You can understand task priorities and the management of tasks.
GOAL L03 • You can explain the difference between a preemptive and a non-preemptive scheduling policy.
GOAL L03 • You can use Percepio Tracealyzer to trace the tasks in a quasi-parallel system.

<!-- V03 – Concurrency (I): Task Synchronization -->
GOAL V03 • You can recognize the problems and the necessity of task synchronization (resources and activities)and inter-process communication (IPC)between two or more tasks.
GOAL V03 • You can explain how semaphoresand mutexes, signals/task notifications, and event registers/event groups, work and how they are used (best practices).
GOAL V03 • You can implement IPC concepts with these RTOS objects in FreeRTOS.

<!-- Lab 04 – Semaphores and Mutexes -->
GOAL L04 • You understand the difference between a semaphore and a mutex.
GOAL L04 • You can synchronize multiple tasks with semaphores.
GOAL L04 • You can protect a section in a task with a mutex.
GOAL L04 • You can use FreeRTOS and the C++ FreeRTOS Wrapper to implement semaphores and mutexes.
GOAL L04 • You can analyze tasks and other FreeRTOS objects (e.g., semaphore, mutex) with Percepio Tracealyzer.
GOAL L04 • You can combine semaphores and mutexes to create a safe access pattern.